Of 414 participants, 88.7% (n=367) had positive practice (score=5-6) in following precautions to avoid COVID-19 (Table I
). Findings indicated pharmacist have higher odds (OR: 2.247, 95% CI: 1.11-4.55, P=0.025) of showing good practice compared to other HCPs (Table II
). Possible explanation is that pharmacist is an emerging profession especially in developing countries like Pakistan, and they are actively involved in educational and training activities to seek knowledge and made themselves competent enough to involve in clinical decision making with other HCPs. Logistic regression also revealed that experienced (> 5years) healthcare professionals were more likely to follow precautionary practices (OR: 10.71, 95% CI: 2.8-40.75, P=0.025), demonstrating this group had skills and experience of dealing with public health emergencies.
